### CSS Nesting

**CSS Nesting** lets you write nested selectors inside parent rules (like Sass).

---

### Basic Nesting

```css
.card {
  background: white;
  padding: 20px;

  & .title {
    font-size: 1.5em;
  }

  & .body {
    color: #666;
  }
}
```

Without nesting:
```css
.card { background: white; padding: 20px; }
.card .title { font-size: 1.5em; }
.card .body { color: #666; }
```

---

### The `&` (Nesting Selector)

`&` represents the parent selector:

```css
.btn {
  background: blue;
  color: white;

  &:hover {
    background: darkblue;
  }

  &.active {
    background: green;
  }

  & .icon {
    margin-right: 8px;
  }
}
```

---

### Nesting Pseudo-Classes

```css
a {
  color: blue;

  &:hover { color: red; }
  &:focus { outline: 2px solid blue; }
  &:visited { color: purple; }
}
```

---

### Nesting Media Queries

```css
.card {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  gap: 20px;

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
  }

  @media (min-width: 1024px) {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr;
  }
}
```

---

### Nesting Combinators

```css
.card {
  & > .header { /* Direct child */ }
  & + .card { /* Adjacent sibling */ }
  & ~ .card { /* General sibling */ }
}
```

---

### @supports Nesting

```css
.card {
  display: flex;

  @supports (display: grid) {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  }
}
```

---

### Browser Support

CSS nesting is supported in:
- Chrome 120+
- Firefox 117+
- Safari 17.2+
- Edge 120+

---

> **Best Practice:** CSS Nesting reduces repetition and keeps related styles together. Don't nest too deeply (max 3 levels).
